{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503553"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:03:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:03:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2044"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2044"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.05,0.08,0.68,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2044"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86814"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2044"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2044"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71086"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"538"},{"type":"tags","id":"1032"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4957"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42444"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44710"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86814"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department after fighting a bushfire on his property. He has superficial burns to his face and singed nasal hairs. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears distressed with laboured breathing and a hoarse voice. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His Glasgow Coma Scale score is 15.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High-flow nasal oxygen","Laryngeal mask airway insertion","Non-invasive ventilation","Endotracheal intubation","Nebulised adrenaline"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of upper airway thermal injury including singed nasal hairs and hoarseness, suggesting impending airway compromise. The priority in burns management is following primary survey principles, with airway being the first consideration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as thermal injury to the upper airway can lead to rapid development of laryngeal oedema. Early intubation is safer and easier than waiting until the airway becomes more compromised. The presence of singed nasal hairs, hoarse voice, and respiratory distress are clear indicators for early definitive airway management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-flow nasal oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E would not protect the airway from the effects of developing oedema, though it might temporarily improve oxygenation. This would be an inadequate intervention given the signs of airway burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaryngeal mask airway\u003C/strong\u003E insertion would not be appropriate as it is not a definitive airway and would not protect against developing laryngeal oedema. Additionally, it may be difficult to position correctly in the setting of facial burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-invasive ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E via face mask would be contraindicated in this situation as it would not protect the airway and could delay necessary intubation. The mask may also cause pain if applied over facial burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E might temporarily reduce upper airway swelling but would not prevent the progression of thermal injury and could give false reassurance. It would be inadequate as primary management given the high risk of airway compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter securing the airway, attention should turn to other aspects of burns management including fluid resuscitation, pain control, and formal burns assessment. The hypotension noted likely reflects hypovolaemia requiring fluid resuscitation according to burns protocols.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Singed nasal hairs and hoarse voice are signs of upper airway thermal injury requiring early intubation","Laryngeal oedema can develop rapidly after thermal airway injury making delayed intubation more difficult","Initial management of burns follows primary survey principles with airway being the first priority"],"references":["Hettiaratchy S, Papini R. Initial management of a major burn: II\u2014assessment and resuscitation. BMJ. 2004;329(7457):101-103.","Walker P, Buehner M, Wood L, Boyer N, Driscoll I, Lundy J et al. Diagnosis and management of inhalation injury: an updated review. Critical Care. 2015;19(1).","Mlcak RP. Inhalation injury from heat, smoke, or chemical irritants. UpToDate. Updated January 2025. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/inhalation-injury-from-heat-smoke-or-chemical-irritants/print"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71086"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2044"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71086"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-24T19:52:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-17T09:12:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2044"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86814"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":nu